\begin_layout Subsubsection
Subshifts of finite type
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Basic defintions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau:\Sigma^{\mathbb{Z}}\to\Sigma^{\mathbb{Z}}$
\end_inset

 be a shift, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 distinct elements (the alphabet).
 A 
\emph on
subshift
\emph default
 or 
\emph on
shift space
\emph default
 is a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda\subset\Sigma^{\mathbb{Z}}$
\end_inset

 that is compact and invariant under the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 Here, compact means that it is closed under the product topology.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A finite string of symbols 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{1}d_{2}\cdots d_{k}\in\Sigma^{*}$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\emph on
block
\emph default
.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be a set of blocks.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{\mathcal{F}}\subset N^{\mathbb{Z}}$
\end_inset

 as the set of strings that do not contain any block in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 at any location.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 is a subshift.
 A subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda\subset N^{\mathbb{Z}}$
\end_inset

 is a subshift if and only if there is some set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda=\Lambda_{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

.
 The elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 are called 
\emph on
forbidden blocks
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A subshift is of finite type (SFT) if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is finite.
 A subshift is 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-step if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}\subset\Sigma^{k+1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is the smallest integer that gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda=\Lambda_{\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

.
 A 1-step SFT is a 
\emph on
topological Markov chain
\emph default
 (TMC).
 All SFT's (of any 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

) can be recoded to a TMC; that is, they are conjugate to a TMC, with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

recoding
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

conjugate
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 defined below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Given a shift space 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

, define the ball 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{k}\left(\Lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 as the set of all blocks of length 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\emph on
language
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $B\left(\Lambda\right)=\bigcup_{k=1}^{\infty}B_{k}\left(\Lambda\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A 
\emph on
finite block code
\emph default
 is a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi:B_{k}\left(\Lambda\right)\to\Sigma^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 mapping blocks of length 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 to some other alphabet 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma^{\prime}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

, it is called a 
\emph on
1-block map
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A 
\emph on
sliding block code
\emph default
 is is a continuous map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:\Lambda\to\Lambda^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 between shift spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda,\Lambda^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, built from alphabets 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma,\Sigma^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, that commutes with the shift, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\circ\tau=\tau\circ\phi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Curtis–Lyndon–Hedlund theorem states that 
\emph on
all
\emph default
 sliding block codes are generated by finite block codes.
 That is, given 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 there exists an integer 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and a finite block code 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\phi\left(x\right)\right]_{i}=\Phi\left(x_{i}x_{i+1}\cdots x_{k}\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{m}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

'th digit in 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\phi\left(x\right)\right]_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

'th digit in 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chandgotia2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If a sliding block code is a bijection, then it is called a 
\emph on
conjugacy
\emph default
.
 If it is a surjection, then it is called a 
\emph on
factor map
\emph default
 or a 
\emph on
factor code
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Combining the above gives an alternate defintion for an SFT.
 A subshift is of finite type if there exists directed graph 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 having 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 vertices, such that the only transitions between successive digits in the
 subshift correspond to edges in the graph.
 That is, for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

 having a digit expansion 
\begin_inset Formula $\cdots d_{k-1}d_{k}d_{k+1}\cdots$
\end_inset

 the only digit transitions 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{k}d_{k+1}$
\end_inset

 are those that correspond to a (directed) edge in the graph.
 Every such graph has a corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $N\times N$
\end_inset

 adjacency matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 with entries 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{ij}=1$
\end_inset

 if there is an edge 
\begin_inset Formula $E:i\mapsto j$
\end_inset

 and zero otherwise.
 The adjacency matrix can be thought of as a Markov chain, and so subshifts
 of finite type earn the name of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

topological Markov chain
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\left(V,E\right)$
\end_inset

 be an undirected graph.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subset V$
\end_inset

.
 The boundary of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial A=\left\{ v\in V\backslash A:\left(a,v\right)\in E,a\in A\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 For directed graphs, we have the incoming and outgoing boundaries.
 Boundaries define nearest-neighbors, and are used to define interaction
 potentials for constructing Gibbs measures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
