\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Basic defintions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A sofic shift is a factor map of an SFT.
 By recoding to a TMC, all sofic shifts are 1-block factor maps of TMC's.
 The graph definition of TMC's above implicitly assumed each vertex label
 was distinct.
 A softic shift maps some of these labels in a way that they are no longer
 distinct.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Sofic shifts correspond to regular languages.
 This follows immediately from the definition in terms of a graph.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Given a word 
\begin_inset Formula $w\in B\left(\Lambda\right)$
\end_inset

, the 
\emph on
follower set
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(w\right)=\left\{ u\in B\left(\Lambda\right):wu\in B\left(\Lambda\right)\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The set of follower sets is 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(\Lambda\right)=\left\{ F\left(w\right):w\in B\left(\Lambda\right)\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 A shift space is sofic if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(\Lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 is finite.
 The predecessor set 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(w\right)$
\end_inset

 is defined analogously; a shift space is sofic iff 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(\Lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 is finite.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 is sofic, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 has dense periodic points.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 has dense periodic points, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 is non-wandering.
 See Chandgotia.
