LatexCommand cite
key "Chandgotia2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Topological Markov fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Toopological Markov fields (TMF) are explored in Chandgotia.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chandgotia2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 TMF's are interesting because they sit 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

in between
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 SFT's and sofic systems: every TMF is sofic; not all sofic systems are
 TMF.
 Also, there are TMF's that are not SFT's.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A 
\emph on
topological Markov field
\emph default
 (TMF) is a shift space 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 for which, given two letters 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\Sigma$
\end_inset

 and two words 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v$
\end_inset

 of the same length 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|u\right|=\left|v\right|$
\end_inset

, then for two strings 
\begin_inset Formula $aub\in B\left(\Lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $xavby\in B\left(\Lambda\right)$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $xauby\in B\left(\Lambda\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This is a 1-step TMF; a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-step TMF replaces 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 by length-
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 strings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A shift space 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 is a TMF if and only if, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

 and all finite cylinders 
\begin_inset Formula $C\subset\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x=y$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial C$
\end_inset

, the point 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\Sigma^{\mathbb{Z}}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z=\begin{cases}
x & \mbox{on }C\cup\partial C\\
y & \mbox{on }\left(C\cup\partial C\right)^{c}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

is also 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\Lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial C$
\end_inset

 is the set of integers in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}\backslash C$
\end_inset

 that are immediately adjacent to elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Measures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A measure is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu:\Lambda\to\mathbb{R}^{+}$
\end_inset

 satisfyingthe usual sigma-additivity axioms on the Borel set.
 Some addtional defintions follow.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A
\emph on
 cylinder set
\emph default
 is a finite subset of the integers 
\begin_inset Formula $C\subset\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and a map 
\begin_inset Formula $c:C\to\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
 The cylinder sets provide the the base of open sets for the topology; together
 with complementation, this gives the Borel sets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A measure is 
\emph on
stationary
\emph default
 if it is shift-invariant, i.e.
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\circ\tau^{-1}=\mu$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A shift space 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
non-wandering
\emph default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall u\in B\left(\Lambda\right)\;\exists v\in B\left(\Lambda\right)\mbox{ s.t. }uvu\in B\left(\Lambda\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The 
\emph on
support of a measure
\emph default
 is the (closed, compact) subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 from which all cylinder sets of zero measure have been removed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The support of any stationary measure is non-wandering.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Markov measures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Markov measures are stationary; general Markov random fields are not.
 Again Chandgotia
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chandgotia2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 provides gruesome details.
 Stationary MRF's are Markov chains.
 Markov chains are Gibbs measures, where Gibbs measures are given by nearest-nei
ghbor interaction potentials.
 The equivalence is more-or-less due to the boundary conditions, which are
 nearest-neighbor conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A 
\emph on
conditional measure
\emph default
 takes the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(C|D\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $C,D$
\end_inset

 are cylinder sets.
 That is, the measure of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is conditionally dependent on 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A Markov chain is a conditional measure of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(d_{1}d_{2}\cdots d_{n}|d_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{1}d_{2}\cdots d_{n}$
\end_inset

 are the digits of a continguous cylinder set.
 That is, the measure for a Markov chain depends only on the previous digit
 (and the cylinder that follows) (and there is no other dependency.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The support of a Markov chain is exactly a TMC.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A Markov random field (MRF) is a conditional measure of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(d_{1}d_{2}\cdots d_{n}|d_{0},d_{n+1}\right)$
\end_inset

 and so the measure depends on both the preceeding and the following digit.
 A kind of two-sideed Markov chain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The support of a stationary MRF is exactly a TMF.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Entropy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Basic defintions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A finite partition 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}=\left\{ P_{1},\cdots,P_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 of a space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a collection of subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{k}\subset X$
\end_inset

 such that they are pair-wise disjoint, up to measure zero: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(P_{i}\cap P_{j}\right)=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\ne j$
\end_inset

, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\bigcup_{k}P_{k}\mod\mu$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(\bigcup_{k}P_{k}\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The entropy of a partion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $H\left(\mathcal{P}\right)=-\sum_{k}\mu\left(P_{k}\right)\ln\mu\left(P_{k}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The measure-theoretic entropy 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mu}\left(\tau,\mathcal{P}\right)$
\end_inset

 of a shift 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 w.r.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h_{\mu}\left(\tau,\mathcal{P}\right)=\lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{1}{n}H\left(\mathcal{P}\vee\cdots\vee\tau^{-n+1}\mathcal{P}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}\vee\cdots\vee\tau^{-n+1}\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 is a partition of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 by shifting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The metric (or measure-theoretic) entropy 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mu}\left(\tau\right)$
\end_inset

 of a shift 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is the supremum of 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mu}\left(\tau,\mathcal{P}\right)$
\end_inset

 over all finite measureable partions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

