\begin_layout Subsection
Shifts with holes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Viewed as a shift space, as opposed to a cut-down binary tree, the trimming
 can be thought of as a punching of holes into the full shift.
 This requires a bit of mental gymnastics.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a,c\right)$
\end_inset

 be an (open) interval on the real number line: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a,c\right)=\left\{ x\,|\,a<x<c\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Given the Bernoulli shift 
\begin_inset Formula $b\left(x\right)=T_{2}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 from eqns 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Bernoulli shift"

\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:downshift"

\end_inset

, consider the set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{I}\left(a,c\right)=\left\{ x\,|\,b^{n}\left(x\right)\notin\left(a,c\right)\mbox{ for any }n\ge0\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

That is, as one iterates on some fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, one requests that no iterate 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{n}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 ever lands in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a,c\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In essence, one has punched a hole in the unit interval; this corresponds
 to a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hole
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the full Bernoulli shift.
 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}\left(a,c\right)$
\end_inset

 is what remains after punching such a hole.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How can this be visualized? Considering the case 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

, its clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}\left(a,c\right)$
\end_inset

 cannot contain 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a,c\right)$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}\left(a,c\right)\cap\left(a,c\right)=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

, the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a,c\right)$
\end_inset

 can come from one of two places: either from 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{a}{2},\frac{c}{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 or from 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{a+1}{2},\frac{c+1}{2}\right)$
\end_inset

, and so neither of these can be in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}\left(a,c\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Continuing, for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

, the intervals 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{a}{4},\frac{c}{4}\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{a+1}{4},\frac{c+1}{4}\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{a+2}{4},\frac{c+2}{4}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{a+3}{4},\frac{c+3}{4}\right)$
\end_inset

 must also be gone.
 Continuing in this fashion, one proceeds with an infinite hole-punch: to
 obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}\left(a,c\right)$
\end_inset

, one just cuts out 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a,c\right)$
\end_inset

 and everything that iterates to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a,c\right)$
\end_inset

.
 For the holes, write
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{H}\left(a,c\right)=\bigcup_{n=0}^{\infty}\bigcup_{k=0}^{2^{n}-1}\left(\frac{a+k}{2^{n}},\frac{c+k}{2^{n}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

and for the interval with the holes punched out: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{I}\left(a,c\right)=\left[0,1\right]\backslash\mathcal{H}\left(a,c\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup$
\end_inset

 denotes set-union and 
\begin_inset Formula $\backslash$
\end_inset

 denotes set subtraction.
 It is not hard to see that, in the end, this forms a contorted Cantor set,
 using the standard midpoint-subtraction algorithm, but with different endpoints.
 The canonical Cantor set is built by taking 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a,c\right)=\left(\frac{1}{3},\frac{2}{3}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that both 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}\left(a,c\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}\left(a,c\right)$
\end_inset

 are subshifts: applying the left-shift to them just returns the same set
 again.
 Bot are invariant under the action of the shift operator.
 In formulas, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b\mathcal{H}\left(a,c\right)=\mathcal{H}\left(a,c\right)
\]

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b\mathcal{I}\left(a,c\right)=\mathcal{I}\left(a,c\right)
\]

\end_inset

where, for notational simplicity, the parenthesis are not written, so that
 for the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, write 
\begin_inset Formula $bS=b\left(S\right)$
\end_inset

.
 As shifts, its more appropriate to view both as sets of bit-sequences,
 so that the proper relationship between one and the other should have been
 written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{I}\left(a,c\right)=\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\omega}\backslash\mathcal{H}\left(a,c\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How should these subshifts be visualized as strings? Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(b_{n}\left(x\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 be the bit sequence generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a<x<c$
\end_inset

.
 The cut operation states that such strings can never occur anywhere in
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}\left(a,c\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Explicitly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}\left(a,c\right)$
\end_inset

 never contains sequences of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{0}d_{1}d_{2}\cdots d_{k}b_{0}\left(x\right)b_{1}\left(x\right)b_{2}\left(x\right)\cdots$
\end_inset

 for any arbitrary leading bits 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{0}d_{1}d_{2}\cdots d_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How should these subshifts be visualized as binary trees? The simplest case
 to visualize is to take 
\begin_inset Formula $a=m/2^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c=\left(m+1\right)/2^{n}$
\end_inset

 being dyadic rationals, for some integers 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, one takes the bit-expansion for both have the same 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 leading bits: one starts at the root of the tree, and walks down the binary
 tree, making left-right moves in accordance with this sequence, and after
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 moves, arrives at a node above a subtree.
 Just cut out this subtree, in it's entirety.
 That's the first cut.
 Now repeat the process, for the left and right subtrees, from off the root,
 
\emph on
ad infinitum
\emph default
.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 not dyadic rationals, the process is more complicated.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 are ordinary rationals, thus having a repeating bit-sequence, one performs
 in the same way, but cyclically walking down the side branches of subtrees.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 irrational, the algorithm is considerably more complicated, and is left
 as an exercise for the reader :-).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A general classification of shifts with holes, for the beta transform, was
 performed by Lyndsey Clark
