\begin_layout Subsection
Generalized compressors and expanders
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The range of the compressor function is a shift with a hole.
 Specifically, for a given 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, the range of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{cpr}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}\left(\frac{\beta}{2},\frac{1}{2}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The construction for shifts with holes can then be applied to construct
 generalized compressor and expander functions.
 One way, which is really rather cheesy, but it works, is to define the
 function
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{dcpr}_{\beta,\gamma}\left(a;x\right)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\left[\frac{1}{\gamma^{n+1}}\sum_{k=0}^{2^{n}-1}\delta\left(x-\frac{a+k}{\beta^{n}}\right)\right]
\]

\end_inset

and then define the generalized compressor as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{cpr}\left(a;x\right)=\int_{0}^{x}\mbox{dcpr}\left(a;y\right)dy
\]

\end_inset

That is, as one walks along the unit interval, from left to right, one picks
 up points with weights on them, obtaining a generalized Devil's staircase
 (Cantor-Vitali) function.
 This generalization does not seem to be terribly useful here, and is left
 to rot.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Self-similarity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Subshifts are, by definition, self-similar.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is a subshift, and 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is the shift operator, then 
\begin_inset Formula $TS=S$
\end_inset

 is the key relation obeyed by a subshift.
 It is fun to see how this actually manifests itself on the unit interval.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So, the two functions cpr and pdr are self-similar.
 The pdr function demonstrates classic period doubling self-similarity:
 namely, under 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=x/2$
\end_inset

, it behaves as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\mbox{pdr}_{\beta}\circ g\right)\left(x\right)=\mbox{pdr}_{\beta}\left(\frac{x}{2}\right)=\frac{1}{\beta}\mbox{pdr}_{\beta}\left(x\right)
\]

\end_inset

while under reflection 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)=1-x$
\end_inset

, it behaves as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\mbox{pdr}_{\beta}\circ r\right)\left(x\right)=\mbox{pdr}_{\beta}\left(1-x\right)=\frac{\beta}{2\left(\beta-1\right)}-\mbox{pdr}_{\beta}\left(x\right)
\]

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{x\to1}\,\mbox{pdr}_{\beta}\left(x\right)=\frac{\beta}{2\left(\beta-1\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The full dyadic monoid is generated by the generators 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 It consists of all finite-length strings of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma=g^{a_{1}}rg^{a_{2}}rg^{a_{3}}r\cdots rg^{a_{m}}
\]

\end_inset

for a finite-length list of positive integers 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a_{1},a_{2},a_{3,}\cdots,a_{m}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Note that this list can be interpreted as a continued fraction; this establishe
s an isomorphism between the continued fractions and the dyadic monoid.
 This isomorphism is conventionally called the Minkowski question-mark function.
 We can be a bit more explicit.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g_{\beta}\left(x\right)=\frac{x}{\beta}
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{\beta}\left(x\right)=\frac{\beta}{2\left(\beta-1\right)}-x
\]

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\beta}\circ r_{\beta}=1$
\end_inset

 so that it is a reflection, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}\left(x\right)=1-x$
\end_inset

 is the reflection of the unit interval.
 For strings of binary digits, the reflection performs the exchange of 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leftrightarrow1$
\end_inset

; its a mirroring symmetry.
 The above relationships then become
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g_{\beta}\circ\mbox{pdr}_{\beta}=\mbox{pdr}_{\beta}\circ g_{2}
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{\beta}\circ\mbox{pdr}_{\beta}=\mbox{pdr}_{\beta}\circ r_{2}
\]

\end_inset

The symmetry under the dyadic monoid is simply the statement that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma_{\beta}\circ\mbox{pdr}_{\beta}=\mbox{pdr}_{\beta}\circ\gamma_{2}
\]

\end_inset

for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 of the above form.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function cpr also exhibits self-similarity, although it alters (expands)
 what happens on the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 axis.
 Several self-similarities are apparent.
 First, for 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le x\le1$
\end_inset

, one has
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{cpr}_{\beta}\left(\frac{x}{2}\right)=\frac{1}{2}\mbox{cpr}_{\beta}\left(\frac{\beta x}{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Equivalently, for 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le y\le\beta/2$
\end_inset

 one can trivially restate the above as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mbox{cpr}_{\beta}\left(\frac{y}{\beta}\right)=\frac{1}{2}\mbox{cpr}_{\beta}\left(y\right)\label{eq:compressor self-sim}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Although this follows trivially, this restatement helps avoid certain confusions
 later in this text.
 This can also be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g_{2}\circ\mbox{cpr}_{\beta}=\mbox{cpr}_{\beta}\circ g_{\beta}
\]

\end_inset

There is obviously no corresponding reflection symmetry.
 The left and right halves are identical to one-another, but offset: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{cpr}_{\beta}\left(\frac{1}{2}+\frac{x}{2}\right)=\frac{1}{2}+\mbox{cpr}_{\beta}\left(\frac{x}{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

It follows that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{cpr}_{\beta}\left(\frac{1}{2}+\frac{y}{\beta}\right)=\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{2}\mbox{cpr}_{\beta}\left(y\right)
\]

\end_inset

Combining the above results into one, one has that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{cpr}_{\beta}\left(\frac{y}{\beta}\right)+\mbox{cpr}_{\beta}\left(\frac{1}{2}+\frac{y}{\beta}\right)=\frac{1}{2}+\mbox{cpr}_{\beta}\left(y\right)
\]

\end_inset

This last form is interesting, as it makes an appearance in relation to
 the transfer operator, defined below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Other things with similar symmetry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The cpr curve is just one that belongs to a class of such curves.
 As an example, one may construct a Takagi (blancmange) curve by iterating
 triangles whose peak is located at 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\beta$
\end_inset

.
 The Takagi curve is an example of a curve transforming under a 3-dimensional
 representation of the dyadic monoid; the cpr curves transforms under a
 two-dimensional representation.
 See my paper on the Takagi curve for details.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Skew-Takagi-Curve"

\end_inset

 shows such a curve.
 Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{tak}_{\beta;w}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

a curve constructed in this fashion.
 The transformation properties of this curve include self-similarity on
 the left, as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{tak}_{\beta;w}\left(\frac{x}{\beta}\right)=x+w\;\mbox{tak}_{\beta;w}\left(x\right)
\]

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le x\le1$
\end_inset

 and self-similarity on the right, as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{tak}_{\beta;w}\left(\frac{1}{\beta}+x\left(1-\frac{1}{\beta}\right)\right)=1-x+w\;\mbox{tak}_{\beta;w}\left(x\right)
\]

\end_inset

Both of these properties follow directly from the construction of the curve;
 they can be taken as the defining equations for the curve.
 That is, the curve can be taken as that function which satisfies these
 two recursion relations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The derivative of the skew Takagi curve is shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Skew-Haar-Wavelet"

\end_inset

