\begin_layout Subsection
Function field arithmetic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In algebraic number theory, one studies function fields over fields of character
istic 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 a prime number.
 Multiplication of a field element by an integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 can be taken as the beta transform, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=n$
\end_inset

 integer, acting on the field.
 Here of course we are working with a field of characteristic zero (the
 reals), or more properly, the sigma algebra of the Cantor set.
 None-the-less, what sort of inspiration can be taken?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is spurred by the observation that the mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}:\mathcal{F\to\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}f=f\circ T^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is richer than just just a linear operator.
 That is, not only does one have the obvious identity 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}\left(af+bg\right)=a\mathcal{L}_{T}f+b\mathcal{L}_{T}g$
\end_inset

 for functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g$
\end_inset

 and constants 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

, but one also has 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}\left(fg\right)=\mathcal{L}_{T}f\cdot\mathcal{L}_{T}g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}\left(f/g\right)=\mathcal{L}_{T}f\,/\,\mathcal{L}_{T}g$
\end_inset

 so that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a function field, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}$
\end_inset

 preserves that structure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Additional algebraic identities follow from the sigma algebra of the product
 topology.
 The product topology implies that one can work with function spaces, e.g.
 measures, for which set intersection and set union behave in a field-like
 way.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 belongs to the discrete or continuous spectrum of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}$
\end_inset

, in the sense that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}e=\lambda e$
\end_inset

, then it also belongs to the spectrum of any iterate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}$
\end_inset

, in the sense that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}^{n}e=\lambda^{n}e$
\end_inset

, and so the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}^{n}$
\end_inset

 form a basis for a vector space.
 By linearity, one can arrange for operators of arbitrary spectrum, in that
 one has (at least formally) that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}a_{n}\mathcal{L}_{T}^{n}\right)e=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}a_{n}\lambda^{n}e
\]

\end_inset

for some arbitrary series of numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset

 (presumably convergent, in order to get reasonable results).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Iterated transfer operator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To understand the nature of the steady-state solution (the Frobenius-Perron
 eigenstate), its is worth iterating on the recurrence relation for it,
 by hand, the first few times.
 To do this, it is convenient to write it in the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{\beta}f\right]\left(y\right)=\frac{\Theta\left(y\right)}{\beta}\left[f\left(\alpha\left(y\right)\right)+f\left(\omega\left(y\right)\right)\right]
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta\left(y\right)=1$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $y\le\beta/2$
\end_inset

 else zero; this is a step function to denote the vanishing for the operator
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $2y>\beta$
\end_inset

.
 (This differs from the use of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta$
\end_inset

 as the Heaviside step function in earlier sections; the intent is the same,
 but the goal is to have a briefer notation here.
 Which is which should be clear from context.) The functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\left(y\right)=y/\beta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\left(y\right)=\frac{1}{2}+\alpha\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

 are convenient shorthands for symbolic iteration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Iterating once gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left[\mathcal{L}^{2}f\right]\left(y\right)= & \frac{\Theta\left(y\right)}{\beta^{2}} & \left[\Theta\left(\alpha\left(y\right)\right)\left[f\left(\alpha^{2}\left(y\right)\right)+f\left(\left(\omega\circ\alpha\right)\left(y\right)\right)\right]+\right.\\
 &  & \left.\Theta\left(\omega\left(y\right)\right)\left[f\left(\left(\alpha\circ\omega\right)\left(y\right)\right)+f\left(\omega^{2}\left(y\right)\right)\right]\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Using a simplified notation 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(y\right)=f\left(\alpha\left(y\right)\right)+f\left(\omega\left(y\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 allows this to be iterated a third time:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left[\mathcal{L}^{3}f\right]\left(y\right)= & \frac{\Theta\left(y\right)}{\beta^{3}} & \left[\Theta\left(\alpha\left(y\right)\right)\left[\Theta\left(\alpha^{2}\left(y\right)\right)g\left(\alpha^{2}\left(y\right)\right)+\Theta\left(\omega\alpha\left(y\right)\right)g\left(\omega\alpha\left(y\right)\right)\right]+\right.\\
 &  & \left.\Theta\left(\omega\left(y\right)\right)\left[\Theta\left(\alpha\omega\left(y\right)\right)g\left(\alpha\omega\left(y\right)\right)+\Theta\left(\omega^{2}\left(y\right)\right)g\left(\omega^{2}\left(y\right)\right)\right]\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and a fourth time, this time omitting the argument, and the various nesting
 parenthesis.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left[\mathcal{L}^{4}f\right]\left(y\right)= & \frac{\Theta\left(y\right)}{\beta^{4}} & \left[\Theta\alpha\Theta\alpha^{2}\left[\Theta\alpha^{3}g\alpha^{3}+\Theta\omega\alpha^{2}g\omega\alpha^{2}\right]+\right.\\
 &  & \Theta\alpha\Theta\omega\alpha\left[\Theta\alpha\omega\alpha g\alpha\omega\alpha+\Theta\omega^{2}\alpha g\omega^{2}\alpha\right]\\
 &  & \Theta\omega\Theta\alpha\omega\left[\Theta\alpha^{2}\omega g\alpha^{2}\omega+\Theta\omega\alpha\omega g\omega\alpha\omega\right]\\
 &  & \left.\Theta\omega\Theta\omega^{2}\left[\Theta\alpha\omega^{2}g\alpha\omega^{2}+\Theta\omega^{3}g\omega^{3}\right]\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Notice that the primary structure is given by a product of step functions.
 This is more conveniently visualized as a tree:
\begin_inset Separator latexpar
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename tree.eps
	width 70col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For any given iteration, the result is the sum of the vertexes at a given
 level, while the product of step functions is the product of the step functions
 in the tree, following the path to each node.
 Because any particular step function might be zero, it effectively acts
 to cut off the tree at that location.
 It is therefore interesting to understand general products of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 functions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is convenient to define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma_{x}\left(y\right)=\frac{x}{2}+\frac{y}{\beta}
\]

\end_inset

so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\left(y\right)=\gamma_{0}\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\left(y\right)=\gamma_{1}\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

, so that a general iterated sequence of intermixed 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

's and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

's can be written uniformly in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 Given a sequence of bits 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}b_{1}b_{2}\cdots b_{n}$
\end_inset

 with each 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}$
\end_inset

 being either zero or one, the iterated sequence of functions can be written
 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\gamma_{b_{0}}\gamma_{b_{1}}\gamma_{b_{2}}\cdots\gamma_{b_{n}}\right)\left(y\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left[b_{0}+\frac{b_{1}}{\beta}+\frac{b_{2}}{\beta^{2}}+\cdots+\frac{b_{n}}{\beta^{n}}\right]+\frac{y}{\beta^{n+1}}\label{eq:not de Rham curve}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

So, for example: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha^{n}\left(y\right)=\frac{y}{\beta^{n}}
\]

\end_inset

while 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega^{2}\left(y\right)=\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{\beta}\left(\frac{1}{2}+\frac{y}{\beta}\right)
\]

\end_inset

and, in general, that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega^{n}\left(y\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left[1+\frac{1}{\beta}+\frac{1}{\beta^{2}}+\cdots\frac{1}{\beta^{n-1}}\right]+\frac{y}{\beta^{n}}
\]

\end_inset

Iterated sequences of pairs of functions, of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{b_{0}}\gamma_{b_{1}}\gamma_{b_{2}}\cdots\gamma_{b_{n}}$
\end_inset

 are reminiscent of de Rham curves, which generalize Cesaro curves and the
 Koch snowflake.
 The proper definition of a de Rham curve assumes the sequence is of infinite
 length, and applies a certain continuity condition, and is generally carried
 out on the complex plane, so that a continuous, nowhere-differentiable
 curve results.
 Here, the curve is distinctly not continuous: eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:not de Rham curve"

\end_inset

 is a finite-length form of the shift series 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:shift series"

\end_inset

 which can be visualized as the expander function pdr 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:expander function"

\end_inset

, as shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Expander-Function"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

