\begin_layout Subsection
Hessenberg wavelet basis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The transfer operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 can be fairly easily brought into Hessenberg matrix form.
 A sequence of of orthonormal functions is constructed in this section;
 when used as a basis, the transfer operator becomes almost upper-diagonal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The trick to the construction is to define wavelets such that the transfer
 operator applied each wavelet causes the end-points of the wavelet to exactly
 line up with the end- or mid-points of previous wavelets, thus avoiding
 the nasty interval-overlap algebra required with the Haar basis.
 This is accomplished by carefully picking the midpoint of the next wavelet
 in the sequence to be located exactly at the discontinuity of the transfer
 operator applied to the previous wavelet.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The construction proceeds as follows.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi_{0}\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
\frac{1}{\sqrt{\beta/2}} & \mbox{for }0\le x\le\beta/2\\
0 & \mbox{for }\beta/2<x\le1
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

Consider 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal L}_{\beta}\psi_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 It is the sum of two parts: two step-functions; one which is constant for
 
\begin_inset Formula $x\le\beta/2$
\end_inset

 and another that is constant for 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{x}{\beta}+\frac{1}{2}\le\frac{\beta}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Solving explicitly for the location of the step, it is 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\beta\left(\beta-1\right)/2$
\end_inset

.
 For convenience, define 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}=\beta\left(\beta-1\right)/2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{0}=\beta/2$
\end_inset

.
 These will anchor a series of midpoints, beginning with 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{-1}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Using the midpoint 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}$
\end_inset

, construct the wavelet
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi_{1}\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
\frac{1}{m_{1}}\sqrt{\frac{m_{1}\left(m_{0}-m_{1}\right)}{m_{0}}} & \mbox{for }0\le x\le m_{1}\\
\frac{-1}{m_{0}-m_{1}}\sqrt{\frac{m_{1}\left(m_{0}-m_{1}\right)}{m_{0}}} & \mbox{for }m_{1}<x\le m_{0}\\
0 & \mbox{for }m_{0}<x\le1
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

Note that this is normalized to unit length: 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{1}\left|\psi_{1}\left(x\right)\right|^{2}dx=1$
\end_inset

 and that it is explicitly orthogonal to the first: 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{1}\psi_{1}\left(x\right)\psi_{0}\left(x\right)dx=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal L}_{\beta}\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 As always, it is the sum of two parts.
 The midpoint of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

 is at 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}=\beta\left(\beta-1\right)/2$
\end_inset

 and this mid-point is mapped to one of two different places.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}<1/2$
\end_inset

 then it is mapped to 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{2}=\beta m_{1}$
\end_inset

 else it maps to 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{2}=\beta\left(m_{1}-1/2\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, if 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}<1/2$
\end_inset

, define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi_{2}\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
0 & \mbox{for }0\le x\le m_{1}\\
\frac{1}{\left(m_{2}-m_{1}\right)}\sqrt{\frac{\left(m_{2}-m_{1}\right)\left(m_{0}-m_{2}\right)}{m_{0}-m_{1}}} & \mbox{for }m_{1}\le x\le m_{2}\\
\frac{-1}{\left(m_{0}-m_{2}\right)}\sqrt{\frac{\left(m_{2}-m_{1}\right)\left(m_{0}-m_{2}\right)}{m_{0}-m_{1}}} & \mbox{for }m_{2}<x\le m_{0}\\
0 & \mbox{for }m_{0}<x\le1
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

else define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi_{2}\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
\frac{1}{m_{2}}\sqrt{\frac{m_{2}\left(m_{2}-m_{1}\right)}{m_{1}}} & \mbox{for }0\le x\le m_{2}\\
\frac{-1}{\left(m_{1}-m_{2}\right)}\sqrt{\frac{m_{2}\left(m_{2}-m_{1}\right)}{m_{1}}} & \mbox{for }m_{2}\le x\le m_{1}\\
0 & \mbox{for }m_{1}<x\le1
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

Because each end of the interval on which 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

 is non-zero lies entirely within one of the constant arms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

, one has, by construction, that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{1}\psi_{2}\left(x\right)\psi_{1}\left(x\right)dx=0$
\end_inset

 (and, of course, 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{1}\psi_{2}\left(x\right)\psi_{0}\left(x\right)dx=0$
\end_inset

.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rest of the basis can be constructed iteratively, based on these examples.
 The midpoints are given by iterating 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:downshift"

\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{0}=\beta/2$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{p}=T_{\beta}\left(m_{p-1}\right)=T_{\beta}^{p}\left(m_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

'th iterate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta/2$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{l}$
\end_inset

 be largest midpoint smaller than 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{p}$
\end_inset

 (and 
\begin_inset Formula $l<p$
\end_inset

); let 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{u}$
\end_inset

 be the smallest midpoint larger than 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{p}$
\end_inset

 (and 
\begin_inset Formula $l<p$
\end_inset

).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{-1}=0$
\end_inset

 initiate the sequence by providing the smallest-possible 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

midpoint
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{0}=\beta/2$
\end_inset

 already provides the largest possible.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\psi_{p}\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
0 & \mbox{for }0\le x\le m_{l}\\
\frac{C_{p}}{\left(m_{p}-m_{l}\right)} & \mbox{for }m_{l}\le x\le m_{p}\\
\frac{-C_{p}}{\left(m_{u}-m_{p}\right)} & \mbox{for }m_{p}<x\le m_{u}\\
0 & \mbox{for }m_{u}<x\le1
\end{cases}\label{eq:Hess-Haar-basis-fn}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

By construction, this has the property that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{1}\psi_{p+1}\left(x\right)\psi_{n}\left(x\right)dx=0$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $n<p+1$
\end_inset

.
 The normalization constant is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{p}=\sqrt{\frac{\left(m_{p}-m_{l}\right)\left(m_{u}-m_{p}\right)}{m_{u}-m_{l}}}
\]

\end_inset

which is determined by requiring that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{1}\left|\psi_{p}\left(x\right)\right|^{2}dx=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
