\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above-defined basis provides the Hessenberg representation for the transfer
 operator.
 Defining
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle n\left|{\cal L}_{\beta}\right|m\right\rangle =\int_{0}^{1}\psi_{n}\left(x\right)\left[\mathcal{L}_{\beta}\psi_{m}\right]\left(x\right)dx\label{eq:hessen-matrix-elts}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

this has the expected Hessenberg form, in that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle n\left|{\cal L}_{\beta}\right|m\right\rangle =0\quad\mbox{ for }n>m+1
\]

\end_inset

This is just one diagonal short of being actually solvable.
 A visualization of the matrix elements is shown in figure 
