\begin_layout Subsection
Completeness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Hessenberg basis construction gives a countable set of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{n}$
\end_inset

 that is an orthonormal basis on the unit interval: 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{1}\psi_{m}\left(x\right)\psi_{n}\left(x\right)dx=\delta_{mn}$
\end_inset

.
 Are they complete? Obviously the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \psi_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 cannot be complete on the unit interval, as they all vanish for 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta/2<x$
\end_inset

.
 Perhaps they are complete on the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,\beta/2]$
\end_inset

, where they are already orthonormal: 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{\beta/2}\psi_{m}\left(x\right)\psi_{n}\left(x\right)dx=\delta_{mn}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A numerical exploration shows that the midpoints 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{p}$
\end_inset

 are dense in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,\beta/2)$
\end_inset

, and so this suggests that the basis should be considered to be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sufficiently complete
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,\beta/2]$
\end_inset

.
 The distribution of the 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{p}$
\end_inset

 follow exactly the distribution of the invariant measure.
 Convergence is uniform to the same degree that the midpoints 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

eventually
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 fill in and become dense in some interval.
 Renyi
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Renyi57"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and Parry
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Parry60"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 do more: they show that the midpoint process is ergodic (Parry points out
 that it's weakly mixing), and provide a formal proof that the distribution
 is one and the same as the invariant measure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above has some exceptions: there are some values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 for which the midpoint 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{0}$
\end_inset

 iterates 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1/2$
\end_inset

, wherupon iteration stops (i.e.
 iterates to zero), or becomes cyclic (forming a periodic orbit).
 Which is which depends on how the point 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

 is treated by the map.
 These values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 are potential 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

trouble spots
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and are explored in greater detail in the next chapter.
 They are dense in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $1<\beta<2$
\end_inset

, but they form a countable set that can be taken to be of measure zero.
 Thus, most 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

most
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 are not problematic.
 Excluding the trouble spots, the Hessenberg basis can be taken to be complete.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Clearly, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{n}$
\end_inset

 span some subspace; do they span the Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}\left[0,\beta/2\right]$
\end_inset

 of square-integrable functions on the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,\beta/2]$
\end_inset

? To what degree can one legitimately write
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta\left(y-x\right)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\psi_{n}\left(y\right)\psi_{n}\left(x\right)
\]

\end_inset

as a resolution of the identity? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The question of completeness dogs some 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

obvious
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 assumptions one wants to make.
 For example, if the set of states is complete, and the resolution of the
 identity holds, then one expects that the transfer operator resolves to
 the iterated function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta\left(y-\left(\beta x\,\mod1\right)\right)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\sum_{m=0}^{\infty}\psi_{n}\left(y\right)\left\langle n\left|{\cal L}_{\beta}\right|m\right\rangle \psi_{m}\left(x\right)
\]

\end_inset

It is fun to verify that the world works as one expects it to work: the
 above can be verified to hold numerically, for sums limited to a finite
 cutoff.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Numerical Eigenvalues
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the apparent sparsity visible in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Hessenberg-Operator-Matrix"

\end_inset

, one might think that the eigenvalue problem is fairly stable, numerically.
 It is not all that much.
 Numerical exploration suggests that the spectrum is on or near a circle
 lying in the complex plane
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This was confirmed with both GSL gsl_eigen_nonsymmv() and Lapack DHSEQR
 solvers, exploring the principle submatrix of various sizes, up to about
 
\begin_inset Formula $2000\times2000$
\end_inset

 entries.
 Both systems agree to at least six decimal places, if not more.
 Both show sporadic eigenvalues off the circle, but these are not numerically
 stable; ergo, the only valid eigenvalues are those on the circle.
 The matrix entries were constructed using the midpoint algorithm, described
 in the last section.
 To verify that they are accurate, several techniques were used: numerical
 integration to confirm orthogonality, and the use of the GnuMP multi-precision
 library to push up accuracy.
\end_layout

\end_inset

, of radius 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\lambda\right|=1/\beta$
\end_inset

 (ignoring, that is, the leading eigenvalue of 1, which is easily found).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To be clear, this is a numerical exploration of the 
\begin_inset Formula $N\times N$
\end_inset

 principle submatrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle n\left|{\cal L}_{\beta}\right|m\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 The eigenvalue problem being posed is to find a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}=\left(v_{k}\right)_{k=0}^{N}$
\end_inset

 that solves 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{m=0}^{N}\left\langle n\left|{\cal L}_{\beta}\right|m\right\rangle v_{m}=\lambda v_{n}
\]

\end_inset

for some constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 (with the set of possible 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 depending on 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, of course).
 
