\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The numerical results suggest a hypothesis that perhaps some fragment of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is unitary, as it is ordinarily the case that when eigenvalues appear on
 the unit circle, it is because an operator is unitary.
 That does not seem to be the case here.
 Specifically, define the Frobenius-Perron eigenvector 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 as the one satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\beta}\rho=\rho$
\end_inset

 and normalizing it to unit length, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \rho\right\Vert =1$
\end_inset

 in the Hilbert (mean-square) norm.
 Define the reduced operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 in terms of the matrix elements
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{\beta}\left\langle n\left|{\cal R}_{\beta}\right|m\right\rangle =\left\langle n\left|{\cal L}_{\beta}\right|m\right\rangle -\left\langle \rho\vert n\right\rangle \left\langle \rho\vert m\right\rangle 
\]

\end_inset

That is, it is just the beta shift operator, with the Frobenius-Perron eigenvect
or removed, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}_{\beta}\rho=0$
\end_inset

 .
 Its rescaled, so that the remaining eigenvectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 lie on the unit circle.
 Is this operator unitary in any way? That is, might either 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}_{\beta}\mathcal{R}_{\beta}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}_{\beta}^{\dagger}\mathcal{R}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 be the identity? Here, the dagger 
\begin_inset Formula $\dagger$
\end_inset

 is just the transpose, as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is purely real.
 Numerical exploration clearly shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is neither unitary on the left nor on the right.
 Not a surprise, but does leave the understanding of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 in a curious situation.
\end_layout

