\begin_layout Subsection
Properties of the theta sequence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define the the set of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

valid
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

acceptable
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 indexes as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{B}=\left\{ n\in\mathbb{N}:\theta_{n}\left(r_{n}\right)=1,p_{n}\left(r_{n}\right)=0\right\} \label{eq:valid index set}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{n}$
\end_inset

 was the acceptance function from eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:theta mask"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 By abuse of notation, write 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{n}=\mathds{1}_{\mathcal{B}}\left(n\right)=\theta\left(n\right)$
\end_inset

 for the membership indicator function for this set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{m}$
\end_inset

 as the pullback of the summatory function for this mask.
 That is, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{m}$
\end_inset

 be the smallest integer for which the following holds:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m=\sum_{n=1}^{\psi_{m}}\theta_{n}
\]

\end_inset

Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{m}$
\end_inset

 encodes the locations of one-bits in the bitmask 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(\psi_{m}\right)=1$
\end_inset

 by definition.
 Equivalently, it counts the total number of one-bits below that location.
 It is convenient to start the sequence at 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{0}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\left(n\right)=\psi_{n}$
\end_inset

 as equivalent notation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several properties are apparent.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For all 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(2^{m}\right)=\theta\left(2^{m}-1\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(m\right)=1$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(2m\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
 By recursion, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(2^{n}m\right)=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is odd, and if 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(m\right)=1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(\left(m-1\right)/2\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
 This is reminiscent of the Collatz conjecture.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(m\right)=0$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(2^{n}\left(2m+1\right)\right)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As noted earlier, the number of valid polynomials of each order are given
 by the necklace counting function 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, one has, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{n=1}^{2^{m}-1}\theta\left(n\right)=\sum_{k=2}^{m+1}M_{k}\equiv S_{m}
\]

\end_inset

Using the 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{m}$
\end_inset

 defined immediately above, one has 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\left(S_{m}\right)=2^{m}-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\left(S_{m}+1\right)=2^{m}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 as a real number is 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\theta_{n}2^{-n}=0.93258880035365\cdots$
\end_inset

.
 At this time, this does not appear in OEIS.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Leaders
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An important subsequence consists of the leaders of the doubling sequences.
 These can be defined in several equivalent ways.
 One property of the bitmask is that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(m\right)=1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(2^{n}m\right)=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 A leader 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is the smallest such 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 at the front of such a doubling sequence: it is either an odd number 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\left(2k+1\right)$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(\lambda\right)=1$
\end_inset

 or it is an even number of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=2^{h}\left(2k+1\right),h>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(2^{h}\left(2k+1\right)\right)=1$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(2^{h-1}\left(2k+1\right)\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 The minimal power 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 defining the leader will be called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

height of the leader
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equivalently, the leaders can be defined as a subsequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{m}$
\end_inset

.
 By definition, one has that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(\psi_{m}\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{m}$
\end_inset

 is odd, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{m}$
\end_inset

 is a leader.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{m}$
\end_inset

 is even, then it is a leader if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(\psi_{m}/2\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a valid index 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{m}$
\end_inset

, it is useful to define a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 that provides the map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Lambda\left(\psi_{m}\right)=2^{h}\left(2\psi_{m}+1\right)\label{eq:Leadership function}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This map is not monotonic: 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda\left(1\right)=3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda\left(2\right)=10$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda\left(3\right)=7$
\end_inset

.
 It is, however, one-to-one, as leaders are always a product of an odd number
 times some power of two.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sorting the leaders into ascending order, the start of the sequence is 1,3,7,10,
13,15,25,29,31,...
 This sequence is not currently known to OEIS.
 It is handy to count from one, and to assign 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}=0$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}=3$
\end_inset

 and so on.
\end_layout

