\begin_layout Standard
All of these integer sequences and roots participate in a number of curious
 relations having a regular form; this is, of course, the whole point of
 listing them in the OEIS.
 This suggests a question: do the known relationships generalize to the
 beta-shift setting?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, the polynomials of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta^{k+1}-\beta-1=0
\]

\end_inset

are the Lamé polynomials, they arise as solutions to Lamé's equation, a
 kind of ellipsoidal harmonic differential equation.
 In the present notation, these correspond to polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(\beta\right)=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2^{k}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another example is the Fibonacci-tribonacci-tetranacci sequence of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

generalized golden means
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 These are the roots of the series for which all 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}=1$
\end_inset

, that is, the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta^{k+1}-\beta^{k}-\beta^{k-1}-\cdots-1=0
\]

\end_inset

In the present notation, these would be the polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(\beta\right)=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2^{k}-1$
\end_inset

.
 Such roots can be rapidly computed by a series provided by Hare, Prodinger
 and Shallit
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hare14"
literal "true"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{\alpha_{k}}=\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{2}\sum_{j=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{j}{j\left(k+1\right) \choose j-1}\frac{1}{2^{j\left(k+1\right)}}
\]

\end_inset

This series is obtained by making good use of the Lagrange inversion formula.
 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{k}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

'th generalized golden mean, i.e.
 the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2^{k}-1}\left(\alpha_{k}\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Can the Hare series be extended to provide the roots 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{n}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(r_{n}\right)=0$
\end_inset

 for general 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another set of observations seem to invoke the theory of complex multiplication
 on elliptic curves, and pose additional questions.
 So:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The tribonacci root 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{3}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{3}=\frac{1}{3}\left(1+\sqrt[3]{19+3\sqrt{33}}+\sqrt[3]{19-3\sqrt{33}}\right)\simeq1.839\cdots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The silver number (plastic number) 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{8}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{8}=\frac{1}{6}\left(\sqrt[3]{108+12\sqrt{69}}+\sqrt[3]{108-12\sqrt{69}}\right)\simeq1.324\cdots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Narayana's cows number 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{2}=\frac{1}{6}\sqrt[3]{116+12\sqrt{93}}+\frac{2}{3\sqrt[3]{116+12\sqrt{93}}}+\frac{1}{3}\simeq1.645\cdots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The root 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{6}$
\end_inset

 is related to the silver number 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{8}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{8}=r_{6}\left(r_{6}-1\right)$
\end_inset

 and is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{6}=\frac{1}{6}\sqrt[3]{108+12\sqrt{69}}+\frac{2}{\left(\sqrt[3]{108+12\sqrt{69}}\right)^{2}}\simeq1.754\cdots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Do the other roots have comparable expressions? To obtain them, is it sufficient
 to articulate the theory of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

complex multiplication
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on elliptic curves? Are these just disguised solutions to Lamé's ellipsoidal
 harmonic differential equation? The appearance of only the cube and square
 roots is certainly suggestive of an underlying process of points on elliptic
 curves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-Fibonacci sequences as shifts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The nature of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-Fibonacci sequences as shift sequences can be emphasized by noting that
 they arise from the iteration of a 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(k+1\right)\times\left(k+1\right)$
\end_inset

 matrix in lower-Hessenberg form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
B=\left[\begin{array}{cccccc}
b_{0} & 1 & 0 & 0 & \cdots & 0\\
b_{1} & 0 & 1 & 0 & \cdots & 0\\
b_{2} & 0 & 0 & 1 & \cdots & 0\\
\vdots & \vdots & \vdots &  & \ddots & \vdots\\
b_{k-1} & 0 & 0 & 0 & \cdots & 1\\
b_{k} & 0 & 0 & 0 & \cdots & 0
\end{array}\right]\label{eq:golden matrix}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

That is, the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

'th element of the sequence is obtained from the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

'th iterate 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{m}$
\end_inset

.
 That such iteration results in integer sequences has long been observed
 in the theory of continued fractions.
 It's useful to work an explicit example.
 For the golden ratio, one has 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 1\\
1 & 0
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

and the iterates are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B^{2}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
2 & 1\\
1 & 1
\end{array}\right],\;B^{3}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
3 & 2\\
2 & 1
\end{array}\right],\;B^{4}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
5 & 3\\
3 & 2
\end{array}\right],\;B^{n}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
F_{n} & F_{n-1}\\
F_{n-1} & F_{n-2}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{n}$
\end_inset

 being the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

'th Fibonacci number, as usual.
 For the general case, after 
\begin_inset Formula $m\ge k-1$
\end_inset

 iterations, one gets the symmetric matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B^{m}=\left[\begin{array}{cccccc}
F_{m}^{\left\{ b\right\} } & F_{m-1}^{\left\{ b\right\} } & F_{m-2}^{\left\{ b\right\} } & \cdots & F_{m-k+1}^{\left\{ b\right\} } & F_{m-k}^{\left\{ b\right\} }\\
F_{m-1}^{\left\{ b\right\} } & F_{m-2}^{\left\{ b\right\} } & F_{m-3}^{\left\{ b\right\} } & \cdots & F_{m-k}^{\left\{ b\right\} } & F_{m-k-1}^{\left\{ b\right\} }\\
F_{m-2}^{\left\{ b\right\} } & F_{m-3}^{\left\{ b\right\} } &  & \cdots\\
\vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots & \vdots\\
F_{m-k+1}^{\left\{ b\right\} } &  &  & \cdots\\
F_{m-k}^{\left\{ b\right\} } &  &  & \cdots &  & F_{m-2k}^{\left\{ b\right\} }
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

so that the top row consists of the latest sequence values.
 When multiplied by the bits, this just generates the next iterate in the
 sequence.
 The upper-diagonal 1's just serve to shift columns over by one, with each
 iteration: that is why it's a shift!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The characteristic polynomial of this matrix is, of course, the polynomial
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det\left[B-xI\right]=\left(-1\right)^{k}p_{n}\left(x\right)
\]

\end_inset

Thus, we can trivially conclude that the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are given by the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This matrix is in lower-Hessenberg form; this makes it obvious that it's
 a shift; a finite shift, in this case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Equivalent labels for orbits
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are many equivalent ways of labeling the various expressions and propertie
s under consideration.
 These are recapped here.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Orbits
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For every given 
\begin_inset Formula $1<\beta<2$
\end_inset

 there is a unique orbit of midpoints 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ m_{p}\right\} $
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{p}=T_{\beta}\left(m_{p-1}\right)=T_{\beta}^{p}\left(m_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{0}=\beta/2$
\end_inset

.
 The orbits are in one-to-one correspondence with 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 The midpoints are the same as the Renyi-Parry seqence; namely 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\beta}^{p}\left(\beta/2\right)=\left(\beta/2\right)t_{\beta}^{p}\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

, recalling here the notation of eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:beta transform"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:invariant measure"

\end_inset

.
 Some orbits are periodic (thus, effectively of finite length), while others
 are ergodic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Orbit encoding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The midpoint generates a unique sequence of bits 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b_{0},b_{1,},\cdots,b_{k},\cdots\right\} $
\end_inset

 given by the left-right moves of the mid-point, as it is iterated.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}=\Theta\left(m_{k}-1/2\right)$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}$
\end_inset

 is one if the midpoint is greater than half, else 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}$
\end_inset

 is zero.
 Each bit-sequence is in one-to-one correspondence with 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 Periodic orbits have finite-length sequences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Monotonicity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The compressor function 
\begin_inset Formula $w\left(\beta\right)=\sum_{k}b_{k}2^{-k}$
\end_inset

 is a monotonically increasing function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, so that values of 
\begin_inset Formula $w\left(\beta\right)$
\end_inset

 are in one-to-one correspondence with 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Polynomial numbering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the orbit is periodic, then there exists a polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(z\right)=z^{k+1}-b_{0}z^{k}-b_{1}z^{k-1}-\cdots-b_{k-1}z-1$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1+\left\lfloor \log_{2}\left(2n+1\right)\right\rfloor $
\end_inset

 being the length of the orbit.
 The positive real root 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{n}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(r_{n}\right)=0$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=r_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 That is, the iteratioin of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{n}$
\end_inset

 will generate the finite-length bit-sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} =\left\{ b_{0},b_{1,},\cdots,b_{k}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is in one-to-one correspondence with the bit sequence, and with the value
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 The integer is explicitly given by 
\begin_inset Formula $2n+1=\sum_{j=0}^{k}2^{j}b_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the orbit is not periodic, there is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)=1-\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}b_{j}\zeta^{j+1}$
\end_inset

 holomorphic on the unit disk, having one unique positive real zero 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(r_{\left\{ b\right\} }\right)=0$
\end_inset

 where this 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\left\{ b\right\} }=1/\beta$
\end_inset

 is the same 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 that generated the bit-sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Iterating 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\left\{ b\right\} }$
\end_inset

 generates 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} $
\end_inset

 is finite, then 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)=\zeta^{k+1}p_{n}\left(1/\zeta\right)$
\end_inset

, so these functions agree on finite-length sequences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Brackets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the orbit is periodic, then there exists a unique bracketing relationship
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\Mapsto n\Mapsfrom\rho$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the polynomial index.
 The left and right bounds 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell,\rho$
\end_inset

 are strictly smaller indexes: 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell<n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho<n$
\end_inset

, and even more strongly, 
\begin_inset Formula $2\ell\le n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2\rho\le n$
\end_inset

 that have the property of bounding the positive real roots of the corresponding
 polynomials: 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\ell}<r_{n}<r_{\rho}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\ell}\left(r_{\ell}\right)=p_{n}\left(r_{n}\right)=p_{\rho}\left(r_{\rho}\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Binary tree
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each bracket is in one-to-one correspondence with a node in the full, unbounded
 binary tree.
 Sub-brackets define left and right subintervals that are disjoint, and
 whose union makes up the whole interval.
 Every node in the full binary tree can be labelled with a unique sequence
 of left-right moves to get to that node.
 This places the brackets (and thus, the polynomials and the roots and the
 mid-point orbits) in unique, one-to-one correspondences with finite-length
 strings of L,R moves.
 Such strings are, in turn, in one-to-one correspondence with the dyadic
 rationals.
 The L,R strings are in one-to-one correspondence with the orbits 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} $
\end_inset

 but they are 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 numerically the same! This are distinct sequences! In particular, all possible
 L,R moves are allowed.
 Only a limited number of orbits 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} $
\end_inset

 are possible, as limited by necklace-counting considerations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Baire sequences
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the orbit is periodic, then there exists a unique integer sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k}\right]$
\end_inset

 such that the index is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 This is a bijection between all valid indexes and all possible finite-length
 sequences.
 Due to the bounding property of the brackets, limits of 
\begin_inset Formula $k\to\infty$
\end_inset

 can be taken, and these limits are unique.
 Thus, all 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 values, including those with non-periodic orbits, can be placed in a one-to-one
 bijection with infinite-length sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots\right]\in\mathbb{N}^{\omega}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Beta-Fibonacci sequences
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the orbit is periodic, then there exists a sequence of integers 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{\{b\}}$
\end_inset

, the beta-Fibonacci sequence, that is in one-to-one correspondence with
 the finite bit sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} =b_{0},b_{1},\cdots,b_{k}$
\end_inset

, and with the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 There are also sequences for each infinite-length orbit 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Shift matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the orbit is periodic, then the finite bit sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} =b_{0},b_{1},\cdots,b_{k}$
\end_inset

 defines a lower-Hessenberg 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

golden shift
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, as shown in eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:golden matrix"

\end_inset

.
 The limit of 
\begin_inset Formula $k\to\infty$
\end_inset

 can be taken in a relatively straight-forward manner, given below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To summarize: any one of these: the integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

, the bracket location in the binary tree, a dyadic rational, a point in
 Baire space, the integer sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{m}^{\left\{ b\right\} }$
\end_inset

, the orbit of midpoints 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{p}=T^{p}\left(\beta/2\right)$
\end_inset

, the orbit encoding 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} $
\end_inset

, the shift matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, the value of the compressor function 
\begin_inset Formula $w\left(\beta\right)$
\end_inset

 and, of course, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 itself can each be used as a stand-in for the others, as they are all in
 one-to-one correspondence.
 Specifying one determines the others; all uniquely map to one-another.
 The formulas that provide maps between each of these can all be given in
 closed form, except for the handful of resursively-defined formulas.
 The recursive formulas are all invertable; thus they are computerable (decidabl
e).
 They are all equivalent labels.
 Fashionably abusing notation, 
\begin_inset Formula $n\equiv p_{n}\left(x\right)\equiv r_{n}\equiv\left\{ b\right\} \equiv F_{m}^{\left\{ b\right\} }\equiv m_{p}\equiv w\left(\beta\right)\equiv\beta\equiv B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An explicit expression relating the orbit encoding and the orbit can be
 read off directly from eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:iterated shift"

\end_inset

.
 Plugging in, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
m_{p}=T_{\beta}^{p+1}\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)=\frac{\beta}{2}\left[\beta^{p+1}-\sum_{j=0}^{p}b_{j}\beta^{p-j}\right]\label{eq:midpoint poly}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $p<k$
\end_inset

 the length of the bit sequence, and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{k}=T_{\beta}^{k+1}\left(\beta/2\right)=\beta p_{n}\left(\beta\right)/2=0$
\end_inset

 terminating, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is the positive root of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Four of the correspondences given above ask for periodic orbits.
 Three of these can be extended to non-periodic orbits in an unambiguous
 and uncontroversial way.
 The extensions are covered in the next two sections.
 The fourth is the numbering 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 of the finite orbits.
 These are countable; there is no way to extend the counting number 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 to the non-periodic orbits.
 Ineed, there ae too many: the non-periodic orbits are uncountable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Infinite-nacci integer sequences 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The beta-Fibonacci integer sequence can be extended to arbitrary (
\emph on
viz.

\emph default
 infinite) length bit sequences, as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{m}^{\{b\}}=\sum_{j=1}^{m}b_{j-1}F_{m-j}^{\{b\}}
\]

\end_inset

starting with 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{0}^{\left\{ b\right\} }=1$
\end_inset

.
 The sum is always finite, but one cannot perform it without first knowing
 at least the first 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 bits of the (now infinite) bit-sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The integer sequence still has the desirable property it had before: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta=\lim_{m\to\infty}\frac{F_{m}^{\{b\}}}{F_{m-1}^{\{b\}}}
\]

\end_inset

Here, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 value is the one associated to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 So, as before, the real number 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 and the bit sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} $
\end_inset

 label exactly the same orbit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Remarkably, one can be sloppy in how one deals with periodic orbits with
 this extention.
 One has two choices that are equivalent: One choice is to truncate, so
 that the bit-sequence ends with all-zeros, effectively rendering it of
 finite length.
 The alternative is to allow it to continue periodically, forever.
 Either form results in the same 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-Fibonacci sequence! 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As an example, consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1.6$
\end_inset

, which is close to the golden ratio, but not quite.
 It has an infinite non-periodic (non-recurring) bit-sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} =101010010100101000000100\cdots$
\end_inset

.
 The generated integer sequence is 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{m}^{\{b\}}=1,1,1,2,3,5,8,12,20,32,51,82,130,209,335,535,\cdots$
\end_inset

 which undershoots the Fibonacci sequence (12 appears, where we expected
 13, and 20 instead of 21, and so on).
 The ratio of the last two is 
\begin_inset Formula $535/335=1.597\cdots$
\end_inset

 and the previous is 
\begin_inset Formula $335/209=1.603\cdots$
\end_inset

 and the ratio of successive elements eventually converges to 1.6.
 By comparison, the Fibonacci sequence is generated by the bit-string 1010101010...
 of alternating ones and zeros.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-Fibonacci representation of the orbits has the remarkable property that
 one does not need some 
\emph on
a priori
\emph default
 mechanism to know if some orbit is periodic or not.
 This dual-representation of periodic orbits is reminiscent of a property
 commonly seen in Cantor space 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 representations of the real number line, where the dyadic rationals (which
 are countable, of course) map to two distinct bit-sequences (one ending
 in all-ones, the other ending in all-zeros).
 A more general setting for this is given in symbolic dynamics, where the
 totally disconnected Bernoulli scheme 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{\omega}$
\end_inset

 can be used to represent elements of certain countable sets two different
 ways.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $N=10$
\end_inset

, one famously has that 1.000...=0.999...
 as an example.
 So likewise here, one can toggle between finite and infinite-periodic strings.
 So, given a finite string 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} =b_{0},b_{1},\cdots,b_{k-1},b_{k}$
\end_inset

 which has, by definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}=1$
\end_inset

, create a new finite string that is twice as long: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b^{\prime}\right\} =b_{0},b_{1},\cdots,b_{k-1},0,b_{0},b_{1},\cdots,b_{k}$
\end_inset

 which necessarily has exactly the same beta-Fiboanacci sequence.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{m}^{\{b^{\prime}\}}=F_{m}^{\{b\}}$
\end_inset

.
 Once can repeat this process 
\emph on
ad infinitum
\emph default
, obtaining an infinite periodic string.
 The difference between these two is simply the difference between a less-than-s
ign, and a less-than-or-equal sign used in the generation of the orbit,
 as noted at the very begining of this chapter.
 We have proven: finite orbits are exactly the same as infinite periodic
 orbits, at least when represented by real numbers and by integer sequences.
 Conversely, the difference between using 
\begin_inset Formula $<$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\le$
\end_inset

 during iteration is immaterial for describing convergents.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Infinite 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-Polynomials
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An infinite polynomial is, of course, an analytic function.
 The goal here is to extend the finite framework.
 The definition of the polynomials above requires a finite bit sequence.
 This can be extended to an asymptotic series, by writing first
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{n}\left(z\right)=z^{k+1}\left(1-b_{0}z^{-1}-b_{1}z^{-2}-\cdots-b_{k}z^{-k-1}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Set 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta=1/z$
\end_inset

 to get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\zeta^{k+1}p_{n}\left(\frac{1}{\zeta}\right)=1-b_{0}\zeta-b_{1}\zeta^{2}-\cdots-b_{k}\zeta^{k+1}
\]

\end_inset

which extends to the holomorphic function
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)=1-\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}b_{j}\zeta^{j+1}
\]

\end_inset

This is manifestly holomorphic on the unit disk, as each coefficient is
 either zero or one.
 It has a positive real zero, of course: 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(1/\beta\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Comparing to eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:holomorphic-disk"

\end_inset

, we see that this is exactly the same function, or rather, it's negative.
 Indeed, following the definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}=d_{n}\left(1/2\right)$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\beta;\zeta\right)=-q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This at last provides a foot in the door for correctly describing the eigenvalue
s of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transfer operator: they are in one-to-one correspondence with the zeros
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 As before, though, this only exposes a discrete spectrum in the region
 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\beta<\left|\lambda\right|\le1$
\end_inset

; if there is any spectrum outside this region, the methods here cannot
 access it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-Hessenberg operator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Extending the golden shift matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 of eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:golden matrix"

\end_inset

 to an infinite-dimensional operator is a bit trickier.
 Of course, one could just declare the matrix elements of the operator to
 be this-and-such, but these matrix elements are with respect to what basis?
 Is the operator even bounded? The answer to the second question is obviously
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

no
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The characteristic equation of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(B-\lambda I\right)=p_{n}\left(\lambda\right)=0$
\end_inset

; the Frobenius-Perron eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta>1$
\end_inset

 is too large, although the 
\begin_inset Formula $k-1=\left\lfloor \log_{2}n\right\rfloor $
\end_inset

 other roots are conveniently arranged near the unit circle, more-or-less
 equidistant from one another.
 The solution is to rescale 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\beta$
\end_inset

.
 The Frobenius-Perron eigenvalue is now one, and the remaining eigenvalues
 distributed near or on a circle of radius 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\beta$
\end_inset

.
 We may as well take the transpose as well, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{\beta}=B^{T}/\beta$
\end_inset

 is in upper-Hessenberg form.
 Rescaled in this way, it now seems safe to declare, by fiat, that the operator
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is the correct extension of the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 to infinite dimensions.
 Just to be explicit: given the bit-sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} $
\end_inset

, the operator
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 has the matrix elements
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left\langle 0\left|\mathcal{H}_{\beta}\right|j\right\rangle  & =\frac{b_{j}}{\beta}\\
\left\langle j+1\left|\mathcal{H}_{\beta}\right|j\right\rangle  & =\frac{1}{\beta}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

with all other entries being zero.
 This is clearly in upper-Hessenberg form, with the subdiagonal providing
 the shift.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Comparing to the upper-Hessenberg form of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 of eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:hessen-matrix-elts"

\end_inset

, and the numerical results on it's eigenvalues, it seems clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 must surely be similar.
 That is, there must be an operator 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 such that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}_{\beta}=S^{-1}\mathcal{H}_{\beta}S
\]

\end_inset

The invariant measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\beta}\rho=\rho$
\end_inset

 is mapped to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=S\rho$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{\beta}\sigma=\sigma$
\end_inset

 is the FP-eigenvector.
 It is easy to write down 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 explicitly: 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=\left(1,\beta^{-1},\beta^{-2},\cdots\right)$
\end_inset

, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{j}=\beta^{-j}$
\end_inset

.
 This is obviously so: the subdiagonal entries of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 act as a shift on 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 and the top row is just
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\left\langle 0\left|\mathcal{H}_{\beta}\right|j\right\rangle \sigma_{j}=\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}b_{j}\beta^{-j-1}=1-q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(\frac{1}{\beta}\right)=1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is no more solvable than 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 in the wavelet basis is, it is certainly much, much easier to work with.
 It also re-affirms the ansatz 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:coherent-first-order"

\end_inset

 for eigenfunctions.
 To be explicit: if 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is a vector satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{\beta}v=\lambda v$
\end_inset

, with vector elements 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{j}$
\end_inset

, then the function
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v\left(x\right)=\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}d_{j}\left(x\right)v_{j}
\]

\end_inset

 is an eigenfunction of the transfer operator: that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\mathcal{L}_{\beta}v\right]\left(x\right)=\lambda v\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

, or, explicitly:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{\beta}\left[v\left(\frac{x}{\beta}\right)+v\left(\frac{x}{\beta}+\frac{1}{2}\right)\right]\Theta\left(\frac{\beta}{2}-x\right)=\lambda v\left(x\right)\label{eq:fundamental-shift}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is just eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:xfer oper"

\end_inset

.
 So, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

, this is just 
\begin_inset Formula $v=\sigma$
\end_inset

 which is just eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:coherent-first-order"

\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1$
\end_inset

, the invariant measure, as always.
 But it also says more: the 
\emph on
only
\emph default
 solutions to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{\beta}v=\lambda v$
\end_inset

 are necessarily of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $v=\left(1,\left(\lambda\beta\right)^{-1},\left(\lambda\beta\right)^{-2},\cdots\right)$
\end_inset

, because the subdiagonal forces this shift.
 To satisfy the the top row of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

, one must have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda=\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\left\langle 0\left|\mathcal{H}_{\beta}\right|j\right\rangle v_{j}=\frac{1}{\beta}\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\frac{b_{j}}{\left(\lambda\beta\right)^{j}}=\lambda\left(1-q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(\frac{1}{\lambda\beta}\right)\right)=\lambda
\]

\end_inset

and so the eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is exactly the eigenvalue that solves the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-series 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(1/\lambda\beta\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 This effectively concludes a proof: the solutions to this series are the
 only eigenvalues of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transfer operator; there are no others.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To recap: periodic orbits have an associated shift matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

; this extends naturally to a shift operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 for non-periodic orbits.
 The shift operator has a sufficiently simple form that it's eigenvectors
 can be explicitly written down in closed form; they are necessarily coherent
 states
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The term 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

coherent states
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 comes from quantum optics: a state that can be written as an analytic series
 over states/vecctors expressed in a different basis.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The top row of the shift operator defines a holomorphic function 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ b\right\} }$
\end_inset

 whose zeros correspond to eigenstates of the shift operator.
 The holomorphic function is determined by the binary digit sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The binary digit sequence is obtained from the iterated midpoint, as 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{j}=d_{j}\left(1/2\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{j}\left(x\right)=1$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $x<T^{n}\left(\beta/2\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This is enough to prove eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fundamental-shift"

\end_inset

 holds for the special value 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 (for 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

).
 It was previously proven that the vanishing of 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ b\right\} }$
\end_inset

 is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, 
\emph on
i.e.

\emph default
 that eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fundamental-shift"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 holds for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Eigenfunctions from finite orbits
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To recap: eigenstates of the transfer operator correspond with the zeros
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)$
\end_inset

, or, more precisely, the zeros for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\zeta\right|\le1$
\end_inset

.
 The reason for this limitation is that the eigenstates are explictly given
 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v\left(x\right)=\sum_{m=0}^{\infty}d_{m}\left(x\right)\zeta^{m}
\]

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta=1/\beta\lambda$
\end_inset

; this is absolutely convergent only for 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\zeta\right|<1$
\end_inset

.
 One might hope to analytically continue this to the entire complex plane,
 but the continuation depends on the digit sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{m}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 One might expect that an analytic continuation is impossible, as the 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{m}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 are ergodic, and thus throws up some kind of essential singularity at 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\zeta\right|=1$
\end_inset

 that cannot be continued past.
 We are lacking in tools and language to discusss this situation.
 Perhaps some insight can be gleaned by examining the periodic orbits...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Case n=1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider first 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=\varphi=1.6180\cdots$
\end_inset

 the golden ratio.
 The corresponding finite beta-polynomial is 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ 11\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)=1-\zeta-\zeta^{2}$
\end_inset

; the infinite series is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q^{\left\{ 1010101\cdots\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)=1-\zeta-\zeta^{3}-\zeta^{5}-\cdots=\left(1-\zeta-\zeta^{2}\right)/\left(1-\zeta^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

which has a positive real zero at 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta=1/\varphi$
\end_inset

 and poles at 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta=\pm1$
\end_inset

.
 The zero corresponds to the FP eigenvalue of one.
 The invariant measure is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v\left(x\right)=\sum_{m=0}^{\infty}\frac{d_{m}\left(x\right)}{\varphi^{m}}=\begin{cases}
\varphi & \mbox{for }0\le x<\frac{1}{2}\\
1 & \mbox{for }\frac{1}{2}\le x<\varphi\\
0 & \mbox{for }\varphi\le x
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

There is a negative real zero at 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta=-\varphi$
\end_inset

, but the eigenfunction summation is not convergent here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Case n=2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

 case has the finite bitstring 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} =101$
\end_inset

 and the periodic bitstring 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} =1001001\cdots$
\end_inset

.
 The corresponding finite beta-polynomial is 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ 101\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)=1-\zeta-\zeta^{3}$
\end_inset

; the infinite series is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q^{\left\{ 1001\cdots\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)=1-\zeta-\zeta^{4}-\zeta^{7}-\cdots=\left(1-\zeta-\zeta^{3}\right)/\left(1-\zeta^{3}\right)
\]

\end_inset

which has a positive real zero at 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta=1/\beta=0.6823\cdots$
\end_inset

 and three poles on the unit circle.
 The FP eigenvalue provides 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1.4655\cdots$
\end_inset

.
 The invariant measure is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v\left(x\right)=\sum_{m=0}^{\infty}\frac{d_{m}\left(x\right)}{\beta^{m}}=\begin{cases}
\frac{\beta}{\beta-1} & \mbox{for }0\le x<T\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)\\
\frac{1}{\beta-1} & \mbox{for }T\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)\le x<\frac{1}{2}\\
\frac{1/\beta}{\beta-1} & \mbox{for }\frac{1}{2}\le x<\beta\\
0 & \mbox{for }\beta\le x
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

There are many equivalent ways to write the invariant measure; the above
 just selected some representatives from the coset of equivalent expressions.
 For example, the third entry could be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1/\beta\left(\beta-1\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Case n=3
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $n=3$
\end_inset

 case has the finite bitstring 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} =111$
\end_inset

 and the periodic bitstring 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} =1101101\cdots$
\end_inset

.
 The corresponding finite beta-polynomial is 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ 111\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)=1-\zeta-\zeta^{2}-\zeta^{3}$
\end_inset

; the infinite series is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q^{\left\{ 110110\cdots\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)=1-\zeta-\zeta^{2}-\zeta^{4}-\cdots=\left(1-\zeta-\zeta^{2}-\zeta^{3}\right)/\left(1-\zeta^{3}\right)
\]

\end_inset

which has a positive real zero at 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta=1/\beta=0.5436\cdots$
\end_inset

 and three poles on the unit circle.
 The FP eigenvalue gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1.8392\cdots$
\end_inset

.
 The invariant measure is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
\frac{\beta}{\beta-1} & \mbox{for }0\le x<\frac{1}{2}\\
\beta & \mbox{for }\frac{1}{2}\le x<T\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)\\
\frac{1}{\beta-1} & \mbox{for }T\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)\le x<\beta\\
0 & \mbox{for }\beta\le x
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Case n=4,6,7
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The pattern gets repetitive.
 There is no case 
\begin_inset Formula $n=5$
\end_inset

, as this is not one of the allowed orbits.
 The bitstrings are those previously listed in tables; they are 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} =1001$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} =1101$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} =1111$
\end_inset

.
 The infinite series is 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ b\cdots\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)=q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)/\left(1-\zeta^{4}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The zeros are as previously listed.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $n=4$
\end_inset

 plateuas are at 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{\beta-1}\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
\beta, & 1, & \frac{1}{\beta}, & \frac{1}{\beta^{2}}\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $n=6$
\end_inset

 plateaus are at 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
\frac{\beta}{\beta-1}, & \frac{\beta^{2}}{\left(\beta^{2}-1\right)\left(\beta-1\right)}, & \beta, & \frac{\beta}{\left(\beta^{2}-1\right)\left(\beta-1\right)}\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $n=7$
\end_inset

 plateaus are at 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
\frac{\beta}{\beta-1}, & \beta, & \frac{\beta+1}{\beta\left(\beta-1\right)}, & \frac{1}{\beta-1}\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Again, the values at the plateaus can be written in many different ways,
 given the finite polynomail.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Case n=16
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $n=16$
\end_inset

 polynomial is the first one to have complex zeros inside the unit disk.
 The finite bitstring is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} =100001$
\end_inset

 and so the polynomial is 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ 100001\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)=1-\zeta-\zeta^{6}$
\end_inset

.
 The positive real root is 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta=0.7780895986786\cdots$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1/\zeta=1.28519903324535\cdots$
\end_inset

.
 The complex zeros are located at 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta=0.965709509\cdots\exp\pm i\pi0.2740452363\cdots$
\end_inset

 which corresponds to the eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0.525107\cdots\pm i0.611100\cdots=0.805718\cdots\exp\pm i\pi0.274045\cdots$
\end_inset

.
 The corresponding eigenfunction is shown immediately below.
\end_layout

