\begin_layout Section
Generating Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-polynomials can be defined via the mask bits 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{n}$
\end_inset

 or via the orbit summatory function 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Corresponding to each is a unique positive real root 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{n}=r_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 This section takes a very short look at the generating functions for these
 sequences.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For any sequnce 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{k}$
\end_inset

, the ordinary generating function is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{OG}\left(c_{k};z\right)=\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}c_{k}z^{k}
\]

\end_inset

The exponential generating function is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{EG}\left(c_{k};z\right)=\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}c_{k}\frac{z^{k}}{n!}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Numerical results include 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{OG}\left(\theta_{k};\frac{1}{2}\right)=1.93258880035365\cdots$
\end_inset

 This is not in OEIS.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{OG}\left(r_{k};\frac{1}{2}\right)=3.0832181425255\cdots$
\end_inset

.
 This also is not in OEIS.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{OG}\left(\psi_{k};\frac{1}{2}\right)=4.14955396300387\cdots$
\end_inset

.
 This also is not in OEIS.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Exploring these visually, on the complex plane, only the EGF is visually
 interesting.
 For both 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{n}$
\end_inset

