\begin_layout Section
Beta Odometer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is clear that the figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Normalization-Integral"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 has some self-similarity properties.
 This section attempts to describe that self-similarity, by identifying
 sequences of discontinuities, and the regions that they bracket.
 This allows a labelling system to be developed for each discontinuity,
 and a bracketing relationship to be given for each self-similar interval.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As always, discontinuities correspond to 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 values that have periodic orbits, and that each periodic orbit is associated
 with a polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=r_{n}$
\end_inset

 is the unique positive real root 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(r_{n}\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Associated to each polynomial is a mask function 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{n}=\theta_{n}\left(r_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 given in eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:theta mask"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Discontinuities are associated to indexes 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 only when 
\begin_inset Formula $1=\theta_{n}$
\end_inset

; the mask function acts both to identify the periodic orbits and also the
 endpoints of a self-similar intervals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The labelling will be for the form of a sequence or string 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\left[m_{1},m_{2},m_{3},\cdots\right]$
\end_inset

 of non-negative integers.
 An example is shown in in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Discontinuity-labels"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, which can be compared to figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Normalization-Integral"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The location 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 of the discontinuity will be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\left(\left[\cdots\right]\right)=\beta\left[\cdots\right]$
\end_inset

, sometimes droping parenthesis if the meaning is clear from context.
 Associated to each sequence is an integer index 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\eta\left(\left[\cdots\right]\right)=\eta\left[\cdots\right]$
\end_inset

.
 By definition, indexes get labels if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $1=\theta_{n}$
\end_inset

; the mask function is the final arbiter for the labels.
 By construction, the identity 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\eta\left(s\right)}\left(\beta\left(s\right)\right)=0$
\end_inset

 must hold for all finite strings 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 The task of this section is to expose and describe the bijection between
 the strings 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 and the corresponding indexes 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\eta\left(s\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

