\begin_layout Standard
From this table, it can be inferred that the recursive sequence index numbering
 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\left[0,m\right]=3\cdot2^{m}$
\end_inset

.
 This corresponds to the mask identity 
\begin_inset Formula $1=\theta\left(3\cdot2^{m}\right)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is sufficient to give a flavor of how bracketing works, and to expose
 an example of index-doubling within a bracketed interval.
 The general form of the bracketing relationship is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k}\right]\Mapsto\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k+1}\right]\Mapsfrom\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k}-1\right]\label{eq:bracketing relation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The case where 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{k}=0$
\end_inset

, resulting in a trailing 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 in the sequence, is handled by means of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

parlor trick
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Sequences with a trailing 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 shorten in length, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\cdots,m,-1\right]=\left[\cdots,m-1\right]$
\end_inset

.
 The final comma disappears, and the trailing digit is decremented by one.
 This may seem like a peculiar rule, but is really just a short-hand to
 simplify the notation for the intervals.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This perhaps most easily understood by plotting actual 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 values for interval endpoints.
 One bracketing relationship is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[1,0,0\right]\Mapsto\left[1,0,0,0\right]\Mapsfrom\left[0\right]$
\end_inset

 which corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $42\Mapsto170\Mapsfrom1$
\end_inset

.
 The parlor trick just allows writing the right-hand side as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[1,0,-1\right]=\left[1,-1\right]=\left[0\right]$
\end_inset

.
 That this is the correct right-hand-side is revealed by plotting 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta\left[1,0,0\right]=1.60135...<\beta\left[1,0,0,0\right]=1.61193...<\beta\left[0\right]=1.61803...
\]

\end_inset

and observing that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0\right]$
\end_inset

 is necessarily the right-hand limit for the interval, as there is no other
 appropriate discontinuity for 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[1,0,0,0\right]$
\end_inset

 to be bounded by.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 is recursive.
 The trailing digit of a sequence always encodes an index doubling.
 This allows a general sequence to be reduced to one with a trailing zero.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eta\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k},n\right]=2^{n}\eta\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k},0\right]
\]

\end_inset

The above is written with an explicit 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

, which will be dropped from subsequent expressions.
 The context should be clear enough: each bracketed form is in one-to-one
 correspondence with it's integer index.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Truncating the trailing zero is more difficult; this is where the index
 mask 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 comes to the forefront.
 The recursion rule to truncate the trailing zero is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k},0\right]=2^{p}\left(2\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k}\right]+1\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is the smallest integer for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(2^{p}\left(2\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k}\right]+1\right)\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
 Finding this value of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 requires a recursive evaluation of the expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 Although 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k}\right]$
\end_inset

 is necessarily a valid index, by construction, it is not generally the
 case that 
\begin_inset Formula $2n+1$
\end_inset

 is valid.
 The simplest example is 
\begin_inset Formula $4=\eta\left[2\right]$
\end_inset

, for which one has 
\begin_inset Formula $2\cdot4+1=9$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(9\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 A glance at the earlier table of valid sequences shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(18\right)=0$
\end_inset

 but 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(36\right)=1$
\end_inset

 and so one has that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[2,0\right]=2^{2}\left(2\left[2\right]+1\right)=2^{2}\left(2^{3}+1\right)=36$
\end_inset

.
 As luck would have it, this rule generalizes, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[k,0\right]=2^{k}\left(2\left[k\right]+1\right)$
\end_inset

; however, such generalizations are not always possible.
 Recursion is controlled by 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is not hard to find many examples for which 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0$
\end_inset

.
 There are many other examples for which 
\begin_inset Formula $p=m_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 In yet other cases, one discovers that 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\sum_{i}m_{i}$
\end_inset

 seems to hold.
 However, none of these are general rules; there is no closed-form expression
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 This may seem frustrating, but in the end, should not be surprising.
 There is no closed-form expression for the mask function 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 that is not recursive.
 The mask 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 encodes the mid-point orbits; the mid-point orbits encode polynomials;
 the real root of the polynomials equals the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 value that is generating that orbit.
 The orbits are in general chaotic, the progress of the mask 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is chaotic as well.
 However, thanks to the recursive defintion of the polynomials given in
 eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:polynomial recursion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

