\begin_layout Subsection
Bijection to Baire Space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The bracketing relationship allows a simple proof that infinite sequences
 (the non-periodic betas), have a unique convergent.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=\beta\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k}\right]$
\end_inset

 be the root of the polynomial determined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 This root can be directly computed as the convergent of a 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-Fibonacci sequence, as will be demonstrated in an upcoming section.
 The relevant point here is that, as numerical values, one has that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k-1}\right]<\beta\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k}\right]<\beta\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k}-1\right]
\]

\end_inset

The inequalities are strict.
 Thus, any given finite-length sequence is bounded above and below by two
 convergents.
 This allows infinite-length sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots\right]$
\end_inset

 to be defined without ambiguity: they are always bounded above and below,
 by increasingly tight bounds, and so have have a unique convergent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The parlor trick turns out to be just the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=2$
\end_inset

 under self-similarity transformations.
 The far-right bound is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[0,0,0,\cdots\right]=\left[-1\right]
\]

\end_inset

The shifted version provides
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k},0,0,\cdots\right]=\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k},-1\right]
\]

\end_inset

which can be interpreted as the two points on either end of a discontinuity.These
 identities are meant to be interpreted as the values of limiting sequences.
 For example, for the second identity, on has that, for a 1 followed by
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 zeros, that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left[1,0,\cdots,0\right]\to & \beta^{2n+3}-\beta^{2n+2}-\beta^{2n}-\cdots-1\\
= & \frac{\left(\beta^{2}-\beta-1\right)\beta^{2n+3}+1}{\beta^{2}-1}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and so in the limit of large 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

, the root of this polynomial approaches 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The extension of finite sequences into infinite ones provides a bijection
 (one-to-one and onto) of all real values 
\begin_inset Formula $1<\beta\le2$
\end_inset

 into Baire space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{N}^{\omega}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{N}=\mathbb{N}_{0}$
\end_inset

 are the non-negative integers.
 
\end_layout

