\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-odometer is defined as the bijection that arises by interpreting a sequence
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k}\right]$
\end_inset

 either as specifying a 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 value or a continued fraction.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 value is of course, the root of the corresponding polynomial; this root
 can be computed directly, as a convergent of a 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-Fibonacci series, as shown in a later section.
 The corresponding continued fraction is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c=c\left(\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots\right]\right)=\dfrac{1}{m_{1}+1+\dfrac{1}{m_{2}+1+\dfrac{1}{\cdots}}}
\]

\end_inset

where this differs from the conventional definition, being off-by-one, because
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{k}$
\end_inset

 can be zero.
 It is visualized in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Beta-odometer"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That the mapping is a bijection is not hard to demonstrate.
 Certainly, for finite-length sequences, continued fractions are rationals;
 each such sequence determines a unique rational, and thus the periodic
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 orbits are mapped to the rationals in this way (thus, the map is an injection).
 Most orbits of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transform are not periodic, however; these map to infinitely long sequences
 of bits in the bit expansion.
 The bracketing relation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bracketing relation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 guarantees that an infinitely sequence is bounded above and below by pairs
 of finite sequences.
 The bound applies not only to the sequences, but also to the corresponding
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 values.
 The bounds are increasingly tight as the sequence lengthens; by standard
 epsilon-delta arguments, the convergent is unique for infinite-length series.
 That is, each distinct non-periodic value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 corresponds to a single, unique infinite sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots\right]$
\end_inset

.
 It is not hard to see that all possible such sequences occur.
 Likewise, every irrational number corresponds to a unique infinite-length
 continued fraction; again, every possible sequence occurs.
 Thus, the odometer provides a bijection between irrationals and non-periodic
 orbits.
 The only difficulty is presented by the rationals: any given rational number
 has several inequivalent continued fraction expansions, and is thus not
 strictly invertable.
 This difficulty is easily swept away by adopting an expansion convention:
 
\emph on
e.g.

\emph default
 by taking the shortest possible continued fraction representation for any
 given rational.
 In this way, one sees that the odometer is a bijection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The use of the word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

odometer
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is perhaps a bit cryptic.
 The rationale for this can be clarified by looking at how it 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rolls over
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The prototypical roll-over occurs at the juncture of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=\varphi=1.618\cdots$
\end_inset

.
 One observes the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\beta\left[0,1\right] & =1.75488\cdots\\
\beta\left[0,2\right] & =1.70490\cdots\\
 & \vdots\\
\beta\left[0,16\right] & =1.61816\cdots\\
\beta\left[0,N\right] & >\varphi\mbox{ for }N\to\infty\\
\beta\left[0\right]=\beta\left[1,-1\right]=\beta\left[1,0,0,\cdots\right] & =\varphi\\
\beta\left[1,0,0,\cdots,1,\cdots\right] & <\varphi
\end{align*}

\end_inset

That is, the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,N\right]$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to\infty$
\end_inset

 rolls over to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[1,0,0,\cdots\right]$
\end_inset

.
 It is this peculiar behavior that merits the name 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

odometer
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unlike the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-adic case, there is no way to increment the odometer by one unit.
 The best one can do is to write out the expansion for 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, decrement by some arbitrarily small 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 and notice that the expansion for 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta-\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 has rolled over at some location.
 The increment is, formally speaking, an infinitesimal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This can be compared to how continued fractions roll over.
 Using our off-by-one notation, write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c\left(\left[0,0,N\right]\right)=\dfrac{1}{1+\dfrac{1}{1+\dfrac{1}{N+1}}}=0.5+\varepsilon
\]

\end_inset

As the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to\infty$
\end_inset

 is taken, this rolls over to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c\left(\left[1,M\right]\right)=\dfrac{1}{2+\dfrac{1}{M+1}}=0.5-\varepsilon
\]

\end_inset

which rolls over to which is, in a sense, backwards: the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[1,N\right]$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to\infty$
\end_inset

 does not roll over to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[2,0,0,\cdots\right]$
\end_inset

 as one might expect some kind of plausible odometer to do, but instead
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,0,N\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-adic odometers are interval maps; they re-arrange countable sequences of
 subintervals of the unit interval.
 Here, likewise, the beta odometer rearranges intervals, at least in the
 sense that rearrangements are disjoint.
 So, the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\varphi,2\right)$
\end_inset

 is mapped to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{1}{2},1\right)$
\end_inset

 albeit in a fractal manner, and likewise each subinterval bounded by the
 descending series of roots to 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{n}-\beta^{n-1}-1=0$
\end_inset

 is mapped to the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{1}{n},\frac{1}{n-1}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 By self-symmetry, the sub-intervals will re-arrange as well.
\end_layout

