\begin_layout Subsubsection
Some continued fraction identities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A short aside to refresh our acquaintance with some continued fraction identitie
s.
 Rationals have two inequivalent finite continued-fraction expansions:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c\left(\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k},0\right]\right)=c\left(\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k}+1\right]\right)
\]

\end_inset

If one allows 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

 in an expansion, then one gets a sequence truncation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c\left(\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k},\infty,m_{k+2},\cdots\right]\right)=c\left(\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k}\right]\right)
\]

\end_inset

The rollover discussed above corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c\left(\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k},0,\infty\right]\right)=c\left(\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k}+1\right]\right)
\]

\end_inset

Defining extended Baire space as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbb{N}\cup\infty\right)^{\omega}$
\end_inset

, then the continued fraction mapping will hit all of the rationals.
 The mapping is not one-to-one, since the first occurence of 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

 terminates the show, and all strings following this collapse onto the same
 rational.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Allowing 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 into the mix provides some oddball identies, including a no-op:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c\left(\left[-1,m_{1},m_{2},\cdots\right]\right)=c\left(\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots\right]\right)
\]

\end_inset

and erasure of the last digit:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c\left(\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k},-1\right]\right)=c\left(\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k-1}\right]\right)
\]

\end_inset

In the middle of the string, one gets a drop:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c\left(\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k},-1,m_{k+2},\cdots\right]\right)=c\left(\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k}+m_{k+2},\cdots\right]\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Vandermonde
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An explicit expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 for the odometer is not obvious.
 Numeric work indicates that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)\approx x\left(1-x/\varphi^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This works because the roots almost line up.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}\left(\beta\right)=\beta^{n+1}-\beta^{n}-1$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{n}$
\end_inset

 be the (one and only) real root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}(\varphi_{n})=0$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{n}=\varphi_{n}-1$
\end_inset

.
 The remapping requires that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(\alpha_{n}\right)=\alpha_{n+1}$
\end_inset

 must hold for 
\begin_inset Formula $n\ge0$
\end_inset

 as an exact identity.
 The above approximate 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 approximately obeys this identity.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 acts as a (right-)shift on the root sequence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Certainly, an analytic series can be obtained; its not clear if this series
 is adequate for describing the self-symmetry.
 Let's proceed anyway.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g\left(x\right)=x+\sum_{n=2}^{\infty}g_{n}x^{n}
\]

\end_inset

This can be solved subject to the above constraints by inverting
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 1 & 1 & \cdots\\
\alpha_{1} & \alpha_{1}^{2} & \alpha_{1}^{3} & \cdots\\
\alpha_{2} & \alpha_{2}^{2} & \alpha_{2}^{3} & \cdots\\
\vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
g_{2}\\
g_{3}\\
\vdots
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{c}
\alpha_{1}\\
\alpha_{2}\\
\alpha_{3}\\
\vdots
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

This matrix is (more or less) a Vandermonde matrix.
 It can be brought into a more explicit form by writing 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{0}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{0}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Then one has
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{ccccc}
1 & \alpha_{0} & \alpha_{0}^{2} & \alpha_{0}^{3} & \cdots\\
1 & \alpha_{1} & \alpha_{1}^{2} & \alpha_{1}^{3} & \cdots\\
1 & \alpha_{2} & \alpha_{2}^{2} & \alpha_{2}^{3} & \cdots\\
\vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
g_{0}\\
g_{1}\\
g_{2}\\
g_{3}\\
\vdots
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{c}
\alpha_{0}\\
\alpha_{1}\\
\alpha_{2}\\
\vdots
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

which is explicitly an (infinite-dimensional) Vandermonde matrix.
 Any given finite Vandermonde matrix has a non-vanishing determinant, and
 is thus invertable.
 Explicit expressions for the inverse can be readily found on the internet.
 As a general rule, Vandermonde matrices are known to be highly ill-conditioned,
 and difficult to invert numerically.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hosseini19"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In principle, we can avoid such difficulties, as we have precise definitions
 for all quantities involved; thus, simpler notation, such as that provided
 by Rawashdeh
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Rawa19"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 overpowers other concerns.
 Still, it is far too complicated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The shift nature of this can be more directly illustrated.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\left[\begin{array}{ccccc}
1 & \alpha_{0} & \alpha_{0}^{2} & \alpha_{0}^{3} & \cdots\\
1 & \alpha_{1} & \alpha_{1}^{2} & \alpha_{1}^{3} & \cdots\\
1 & \alpha_{2} & \alpha_{2}^{2} & \alpha_{2}^{3} & \cdots\\
\vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T=\left[\begin{array}{ccccc}
0 & 1 & 0 & 0 & \cdots\\
0 & 0 & 1 & 0 & \cdots\\
0 & 0 & 0 & 1 & \cdots\\
\vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha=\left[\begin{array}{c}
\alpha_{0}\\
\alpha_{1}\\
\alpha_{2}\\
\vdots
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

Then the above eqn takes the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Ag=T\alpha=TA\left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
1\\
0\\
\vdots
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

Presuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is invertable, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g=A^{-1}TA\left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
1\\
0\\
\vdots
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

So the desired solution picks out one column from a shift that uses a Vandermond
e matrix as the similarity transform.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rows of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 are the iterates of the monomials in a quotient ring.
 So, first of all, the polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}\left(\beta\right)$
\end_inset

 are irreducible (over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

; they have one and only one real root; that root is not a rational number).
 The quotient ring 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}\left[\beta\right]/f_{n}$
\end_inset

 is thus a field.
 It's also a vector space, spanned by the monomials 
\begin_inset Formula $1,\beta,\beta^{2},\cdots,\beta^{n}$
\end_inset

 as basis vectors, where modulo 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}$
\end_inset

 means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{n+1}=\beta^{n}+1$
\end_inset

.
 Of course, the root 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{n}$
\end_inset

 is an algebraic element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}\left[\beta\right]/f_{n}$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{n}$
\end_inset

 is a simple extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

first ring isomorphism theorem
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 states that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}\left[\beta\right]/f_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{n}$
\end_inset

 are isomorphic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Note, BTW, that we've broken our convention for 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 used in the rest of the paper.
 Everywhere where we have 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 in this section, it should actually be 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{n}$
\end_inset

 to be consistent with earlier notation.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What is the orbit of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{n}^{m}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $m\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

? Numerically, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{n}>1$
\end_inset

, taking its powers will clearly blow up.
 The corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-Fibonacci sequence is 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{m+1}^{\left(n\right)}=F_{m}^{\left(n\right)}+F_{m-n}^{\left(n\right)}$
\end_inset

 and so one can immediately write 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{n}^{m}=F_{m}^{\left(n\right)}\varphi_{n}^{n}+F_{m-1}^{\left(n\right)}\varphi_{n}^{n-1}+\cdots+F_{m-n}^{\left(n\right)}\varphi_{n}^{0}$
\end_inset

 as the orbit of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{n}^{m}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the present case, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}=\varphi_{1}-1=\varphi-1$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}^{2}=1-\alpha_{1}=2-\varphi$
\end_inset

, and onward: 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}^{3}=2\alpha_{1}-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}^{4}=2-3\alpha_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}^{5}=5\alpha_{1}-3$
