\begin_layout Subsection
Multiplicative Shifts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A multiplicative shift is a shift assembled as an product of functions.
 The most famous of these is the generating function for integer partitions
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P\left(z\right)=\prod_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{\left(1-z^{n}\right)}
\]

\end_inset

Similarly products occur for the necklace counting functions, most famously
 the cyclotomic identity
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{1-\beta z}=\prod_{j=1}^{\infty}\left(\frac{1}{1-z^{j}}\right)^{M(\beta,j)}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $M\left(\beta,j\right)$
\end_inset

 the necklace polynomial.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A far more obscure product expresses the Minkowski measure
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vep-mink2008"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, given as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
?^{\prime}\left(x\right)=\prod_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{A^{\prime}\circ A^{n}\left(x\right)}{2}
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
\frac{x}{1-x} & \mbox{ for }0\le x<\frac{1}{2}\\
\frac{2x-1}{x} & \mbox{ for }\frac{1}{2}\le x\le1
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 being the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{n}$
\end_inset

 being the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

'th iterate.
 The Minkowski measure integrates to the Minkowski Question Mark function
 
\begin_inset Formula $?\left(y\right)=\int_{0}^{y}?^{\prime}\left(x\right)dx$
\end_inset

; it is the prototypical 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

multi-fractal measure
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (although there really is nothing 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
