\begin_inset Formula $z=\lambda$
\end_inset

 is part of the domain of the Bergman space, then one must conclude that
 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(z\right)=0$
\end_inset

 everywhere.
 That is, right-eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 correspond to functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(z\right)$
\end_inset

 that are vanishing.
 To invent a new name, by analogy to the Fredholm alternative, perhaps this
 can be called the Bergman alternative.
\end_layout

