,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{n}\left(z\right)=\sum_{k=0}^{n}p_{nk}z^{k}
\]

\end_inset

This defines an infinite matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}=\left[p_{nk}\right]$
\end_inset

, provided that the coefficients are extended so that 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{nk}=0$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $k>n$
\end_inset

.
 This matrix is manifestly lower-triangular.
 Writing vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{z}=\left(z^{n}\right)_{n=0}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{p}=\left(p_{n}\left(z\right)\right)_{n=0}^{\infty}$
