\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{n+1,n}p_{n+1,j}=p_{n,j-1}-\sum_{k=0}^{n}A_{kn}p_{kj}
\]

\end_inset

The starting conditions are 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{00}=1$
\end_inset

.
 To handle the 
\begin_inset Formula $j=0$
\end_inset

 case in the above, set 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n,-1}=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 is lower triangular, its inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}^{-1}\equiv\mathcal{R}=\left[r_{kn}\right]$
\end_inset

 can be obtained explicitly.
 Along the diagonal, one has 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{nn}=1/p_{nn}$
\end_inset

 while the lower triangular form means 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{kn}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k<n$
\end_inset

.
 For the remaining entries 
\begin_inset Formula $m<n$
\end_inset

, one has 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=\sum_{k=m}^{n}p_{nk}r_{km}
\]

\end_inset

This can be solved in a finite number of iterations on 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{nn}r_{nm}=-\sum_{k=m}^{n-1}p_{nk}r_{km}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above avoids questions of convergence, or any notion of the spaces on
 which the matrices or operators might act.
 The norm to be used for 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{p}$
\end_inset

 is not specified.
 This is appropriate at this stage: it is the algebraic manipulations that
 are interesting, at this point, rather than the spaces on which the matrices/op
erators might act.
 One can invent several kinds of norms that might be applicable, but there
 is no particular reason to believe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{p}$
\end_inset

 might have a finite norm.
 Likewise, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 may not have a finite norm.
 For the case of the Hessenberg operator originating with the beta shift
 operator, it does not; the individual matrix elements 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{nm}$
\end_inset

 increase without bound.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 is an infinite matrix, but it is not clear that it is also an operator.
 If it is, it is certainly not a compact operator.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some of the poor behavior can be brought under control by factoring 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}=\mathcal{DN}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

 being unitriangular (all ones on the diagonal) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

