\begin_layout Section
The Jacobi Operator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a Borel measure on the real number line, one can find a sequence of
 polynomials that are orthonormal with respect to that measure.
 These polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 are coupled together by a three-term recurrence equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
xp_{n}\left(x\right)=a_{n+1}p_{n+1}\left(x\right)+b_{n}p_{n}\left(x\right)+a_{n}p_{n-1}\left(x\right)
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}\left(x\right)=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{-1}\left(x\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 This recurrence relation can be taken to be an operator, known as the Jacobi
 operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{J}$
\end_inset

, acting on vectors consisting of the polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(x\right)=\left\{ p_{n}\left(x\right)\right\} $
\end_inset

 so that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\mathcal{J}p\right]\left(x\right)=xp\left(x\right)
\]

\end_inset

so that 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvector of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{J}$
\end_inset

 with eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 The two sequences of coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ a_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 form three diagonals of the operator, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ a_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 running down the center, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 the two diagonals on either side
